#. Tag: title
#: systemd.xml:1879
#, no-c-format
msgid "&systemd; timer units"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1881
#, no-c-format
msgid "Similar to cron, &systemd; timer units provide a mechanism for scheduling jobs on Linux. Although &systemd; timer units serve the same purpose as cron, they offer several advantages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1888
#, no-c-format
msgid "Jobs scheduled using a timer unit can depend on other &systemd; services."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1893
#, no-c-format
msgid "Timer units are treated as regular &systemd; services, so can be managed with <command>systemctl</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1898
#, no-c-format
msgid "Timers can be realtime and monotonic."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1903
#, no-c-format
msgid "Time units are logged to the &systemd; journal, which makes it easier to monitor and troubleshoot them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1909
#, no-c-format
msgid "&systemd; timer units are identified by the <literal>.timer</literal> file name extension."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: systemd.xml:1914
#, no-c-format
msgid "&systemd; timer types"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1915
#, no-c-format
msgid "Timer units can use monotonic and realtime timers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1920
#, no-c-format
msgid "Similar to cronjobs, realtime timers are triggered on calendar events. Realtime timers are defined using the option <option>OnCalendar</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1926
#, no-c-format
msgid "Monotonic timers are triggered at a specified time elapsed from a certain starting point. The latter could be a system boot or system unit activation event. There are several options for defining monotonic timers including <option>OnBootSec</option> , <option>OnUnitActiveSec</option> , and <option>OnTypeSec</option> . Monotonic timers are not persistent, and they are reset after each reboot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: systemd.xml:1937
#, no-c-format
msgid "&systemd; timers and service units"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: systemd.xml:1938
#, no-c-format
msgid "Every timer unit must have a corresponding &systemd; unit file it controls. In other words, a <filename>.timer</filename> file activates and manages the corresponding <filename>.service</filename> file. When used with a timer, the <filename>.service</filename> file does not require an <literal>[Install]</literal> section, as the service is managed by the timer."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: systemd.xml:1946
#, no-c-format
